tweet: To my knowledge, no one has written a book specifically about this extraordinary story, which had immense implications for the American economy, government and society. Historians need to jump on this. It's difficult because the sources are few and sketchy.

name: Dr. Sean Munger
tweet: ...paid little attention to the "tools" grift until it already accounted for over 2/3 of their revenue. In a panic, in 1983 they (Amway founders) tried to shut it down...but failed. There was a battle, but the "tools" dons won. Little is known about this.

name: Dr. Sean Munger
tweet: This business should be entirely illegal. But Amway, fighting for its own survival against the FTC, bought the right politicians (Gerald Ford and Ronald Reagan) and managed to survive by the skin of its teeth. Distracted by this battle, the Amway founders...

name: Dr. Sean Munger
tweet: Essentially this guy and a partner hijacked the entire Amway corporation to turn it into this tape-pushing business. This became a $100 million plus racket in 1970s dollars...controlled entirely by two families, much like the Mafia.

name: Dr. Sean Munger
tweet: Amway, founded in 1959, never really functioned economically. In about 1966, one man from Rome, NY realized this and figured out (largely by trial and error) that the real way to make money was to sell motivational tapes, seminars and rallies. Those are the "tools."

name: Dr. Sean Munger
tweet: ...are written from the standpoint of consumer advice (don't get involved) and stress the fundamental impossibility of making money under the main system that most people who get into Amway encounter. But there's another story here.

name: Dr. Sean Munger
tweet: There's a lot written on Amway and MLMs in general and the anti-MLM community is more robust than it's ever been. Most people know that Amway, one of the original MLMs, is a pyramid scheme. There are many blogs and a few books out there about it but most... (cont'd)
